        This API provides a mechanism for dynamic API invocation. This method can be used to invoke any of the APIs exposed by this interface in a dynamic fashion. The standard way to achieve dynamic invocation in java is through the reflection api. This method does just that, saving the programmer the work of writing introspection code. The programmer needs just supply the api name and the input document as parameters to this function. This method cannot, however, be used to invoke the flow services that are configured in the interoperability configuration. To execute flow services use the executeFlow method.

        Pre Conditions:
        An environment handle must be obtained using the createEnvironment() API.

        Post Conditions:
        None.
        Parameters:
        env - Environment handle returned by the createEnvironment() API.
        apiName - Name of the API being invoked.
        inDoc - Input to the invoked API.
        Returns:
        Output Document returned by the invoked API.

        This API provides a mechanism for executing a synchronous flow service. A synchronous flow service is a plug-n-play feature provided by the Interoperability framework. A synchronous flow can be configured to route a document through various service components, such as transform the document via an XSL, call one or more custom apis, , stage the document into a queue or DB, and so on. Read the platform configuration guide for a detailed introduction to flow services and their configuration.

        Pre Conditions:
        An environment handle must be obtained using the createEnvironment() API.

        Post Conditions:
        None.
        Parameters:
        env - Environment handle returned by the createEnvironment() API.
        apiName - Name of the flow being invoked.
        inDoc - Input to the flow. This has to be a valid XML document.
        Returns:
        Output Document returned by the flow. This may be null
        Throws:
